  &lt;p id="NPf9gM"&gt;The Quibi story is both short and epic. In January 2020, company founder Jeffrey Katzenberg and CEO Meg Whitman were onstage at CES delivering an hour-long presentation on how they were &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/1/8/21056315/quibi-ces-2020-launch-meg-whitman-jeffrey-katzenberg-turnstyle-technology-shows-preview"&gt;about to upend the entertainment business&lt;/a&gt;. They’d developed new tech, signed up seemingly half the stars in Hollywood, and had raised more than a billion dollars to pull it off. By October, it was all over. &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/10/22/21528404/quibi-shut-down-cost-subscribers-content-tv-movies-katzenberg-whitman-tiktok-netflix"&gt;Quibi was shutting down&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div id="gOQVjK"&gt;

&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;div id="nxkB8S"&gt;
