  &lt;p id="CTntzs"&gt;Nvidia is on a mission to eliminate its legacy Control Panel and GeForce Experience apps and combine them into a single new Nvidia app. That effort &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/22/24079529/nvidia-app-geforce-experience-control-panel-windows"&gt;started earlier this year&lt;/a&gt;, and a &lt;a href="https://go.redirectingat.com?id=66960X1514734&amp;amp;xs=1&amp;amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.nvidia.com%2Fen-us%2Fgeforce%2Fnews%2Fnvidia-app-beta-update-rtx-vsr-hdr-controls-and-more%2F&amp;amp;referrer=theverge.com&amp;amp;sref=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.theverge.com%2F2024%2F8%2F6%2F24213585%2Fnvidia-app-update-rtx-video-display-features" rel="sponsored nofollow noopener" target="_blank"&gt;new beta update&lt;/a&gt; today adds display settings, RTX Video Super Resolution, RTX Video HDR sliders, and more features.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="VUuKII"&gt;The new displays section lets you adjust resolution, refresh rate, and orientation controls for connected monitors or TVs. The controls are similar to what exists inside the Settings section of Windows 10 or 11, but this now lets you adjust all your GPU settings in a single location.&lt;/p&gt;
