  &lt;p id="CV0I0z"&gt;Red Ventures is selling CNET to Ziff Davis, the digital media and internet company that owns other notable tech publications like &lt;em&gt;Mashable&lt;/em&gt;, &lt;em&gt;IGN&lt;/em&gt;, and &lt;em&gt;Lifehacker&lt;/em&gt;. Ziff Davis’ chief executive, Vivek Shah, &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/08/06/business/media/cnet-ziff-davis.html"&gt;confirmed the acquisition&lt;/a&gt; to &lt;em&gt;The New York Times&lt;/em&gt; on Tuesday.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="apcXzs"&gt;Ironically, back in 2000, it was CNET Networks Inc. that &lt;a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB963981866275420328"&gt;paid $1.6 billion&lt;/a&gt; to acquire the then-tech-publishing-behemoth Ziff-Davis Inc. and its online services company, ZDNet. So much has happened in the last two decades in the form of divestments and realignments that today’s inverted purchase isn’t as ouroboric as it might seem. In 2020, &lt;a href="https://www.redventures.com/press/press-releases/red-ventures-to-acquire-cnet-media-group"&gt;Red Ventures acquired CNET&lt;/a&gt; along with a few other smaller properties for $500 million.&lt;/p&gt;
